</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Creation of isotropic volumes with submillimeter multidetector computed tomography (CT) has expanded interpretative practice to routinely include two-dimensional (2D) and three-dimensional (3D) postprocessing techniques. Currently, 2D multiplanar reformatting, maximum intensity projection, and 3D volume rendering are available on most workstations. Only volume rendering yields a 3D display that depicts all tissue types from any orientation. Utility is not limited to vascular applications, as 3D volume rendering can be used to evaluate neoplastic, infectious, and inflammatory processes that affect the small-bowel mesentery. Specifically, interactive interpretation of multidetector CT data sets with volume rendering can help characterize nonvascular mesenteric disease, elucidate its extent through more comprehensive display, and facilitate the identification of complications.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085113">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085113">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g01x.jpeg" height="1521" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Coronal multiplanar reformatted (MPR) image shows normal lymph nodes (arrows) in the small-bowel mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g02a.jpeg" height="1674" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Coronal VR image shows normal small bowel and mesentery. <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image obtained with posterior translation of the clip plane shows the superior mesenteric artery and branches coursing through mesenteric fat. Fat, blood vessels, and bowel loops are more easily differentiated with 3D volume rendering than with 2D reformatting (compare with <a href="#F1">Fig 1</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g02b.jpeg" height="1661" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Coronal VR image shows normal small bowel and mesentery. <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image obtained with posterior translation of the clip plane shows the superior mesenteric artery and branches coursing through mesenteric fat. Fat, blood vessels, and bowel loops are more easily differentiated with 3D volume rendering than with 2D reformatting (compare with <a href="#F1">Fig 1</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g03a.jpeg" height="1476" width="1341" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Acute Crohn disease in a 22-year-old woman after bowel resection and ileocecal anastomosis creation. Coronal CT images show increased enhancement due to hyperemia of the bowel, a sign of active disease. Prominent vascularity of the transverse mesocolon is visible in <b>a</b>, a VR image, but more readily appreciated in <b>b</b>, a MIP image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g03b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1386" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Acute Crohn disease in a 22-year-old woman after bowel resection and ileocecal anastomosis creation. Coronal CT images show increased enhancement due to hyperemia of the bowel, a sign of active disease. Prominent vascularity of the transverse mesocolon is visible in <b>a</b>, a VR image, but more readily appreciated in <b>b</b>, a MIP image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g04a.jpeg" height="1521" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Mesenteric panniculitis in a 45-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b, c)</b> CT images show multiple small nodes and prominent vessels in the right lower quadrant of the mesentery (arrows in <b>a</b>). Both coronal images depict the extent of mesenteric involvement more clearly than the axial image, with the findings being most conspicuous in <b>c</b>. Because voxels containing high attenuation were selected for the MIP, more enhancement due to oral contrast material is seen in <b>c</b> than in <b>b</b>. Note that the use of positive oral contrast material in this case might have caused the vasculature in <b>c</b> to be obscured. For both coronal views, clip plane editing was performed to remove bowel loops anterior and posterior to the selected image volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g04b.jpeg" height="1476" width="1411" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Mesenteric panniculitis in a 45-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b, c)</b> CT images show multiple small nodes and prominent vessels in the right lower quadrant of the mesentery (arrows in <b>a</b>). Both coronal images depict the extent of mesenteric involvement more clearly than the axial image, with the findings being most conspicuous in <b>c</b>. Because voxels containing high attenuation were selected for the MIP, more enhancement due to oral contrast material is seen in <b>c</b> than in <b>b</b>. Note that the use of positive oral contrast material in this case might have caused the vasculature in <b>c</b> to be obscured. For both coronal views, clip plane editing was performed to remove bowel loops anterior and posterior to the selected image volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g04c.jpeg" height="1278" width="1262" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Mesenteric panniculitis in a 45-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b, c)</b> CT images show multiple small nodes and prominent vessels in the right lower quadrant of the mesentery (arrows in <b>a</b>). Both coronal images depict the extent of mesenteric involvement more clearly than the axial image, with the findings being most conspicuous in <b>c</b>. Because voxels containing high attenuation were selected for the MIP, more enhancement due to oral contrast material is seen in <b>c</b> than in <b>b</b>. Note that the use of positive oral contrast material in this case might have caused the vasculature in <b>c</b> to be obscured. For both coronal views, clip plane editing was performed to remove bowel loops anterior and posterior to the selected image volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g05x.jpeg" height="1552" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5.</b>  Mesenteric cysts in the region of the lesser peritoneal sac in a 60-year-old woman. Coronal VR image shows two thin-walled cysts (arrows) with focal mural calcification, findings that are easily separable from the adjacent stomach and pancreas in the 3D view. The differential diagnosis included pseudocyst, lymphangioma, and enteric or mesothelial cyst. There was no history of pancreatitis, and the pancreatic parenchyma and duct appeared normal at CT. Endoscopic US with aspiration revealed mucus, rare benign granular cells, and histiocytes, findings indicative of a benign cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g06x.jpeg" height="1318" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Left-upper-quadrant abdominal mass in a 67-year-old woman. Coronal VR image demonstrates a homogeneous, hypoattenuating, multilocular cyst (white arrows) that surrounds the splenic artery and vein without invasion or displacement. The cystic septa and vessels (black arrows) that course between the locules are characteristic of lymphangioma. Volume rendering provides a more complete view of the relation of the mass to the vasculature.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g07x.jpeg" height="1638" width="1338" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  Coronal VR image, obtained in a 49-year-old woman with abdominal pain 1 year after trauma from a motorcycle accident, shows a large cystic mass that is separate from the liver and has displaced mesenteric vessels, small bowel, and ascending colon. The thick wall of the cyst is suggestive of a pseudocyst due to hematoma, chronic abscess, previously infected mesenteric cyst, cystadenoma, or sarcoma. At surgery, the mass was found in a retroperitoneal location in the ascending colon mesentery. Pathologic analysis showed it to be a mucinous cystadenoma. Results of immunostaining were suggestive of origin from ectopic ovarian tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g08a.jpeg" height="1530" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Postoperative abscess and anastomotic leak in a 64-year-old man with worsening pneumoperitoneum after bowel resection for Crohn disease. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and coronal MPR <b>(b)</b> images show rimlike enhancement of a fluid collection (arrows) adherent to bowel (arrowheads), findings suggestive of an intraloop abscess and anastomotic leak, the presence of which was confirmed at surgery. Because the surrounding bowel loops course along the z-axis, coronal images best depict the relation between the small bowel and abscess. (Low attenuation in the inferior pole of the spleen is due to infarction.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g08b.jpeg" height="1494" width="1486" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Postoperative abscess and anastomotic leak in a 64-year-old man with worsening pneumoperitoneum after bowel resection for Crohn disease. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and coronal MPR <b>(b)</b> images show rimlike enhancement of a fluid collection (arrows) adherent to bowel (arrowheads), findings suggestive of an intraloop abscess and anastomotic leak, the presence of which was confirmed at surgery. Because the surrounding bowel loops course along the z-axis, coronal images best depict the relation between the small bowel and abscess. (Low attenuation in the inferior pole of the spleen is due to infarction.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g09x.jpeg" height="1494" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma involving the small-bowel mesentery in an 86-year-old woman. Coronal VR image shows tumor extension along the mesenteric vessels, with encasement of a long segment of the superior mesenteric artery (white arrows) and near-occlusion of the superior mesenteric vein (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g10x.jpeg" height="1494" width="1233" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Variations in the CT appearance of lymphoma. Mantle cell lymphoma in a 55-year-old man. Coronal VR image depicts a homogeneous hypoattenuating mesenteric mass (white arrows) that encases branches of the superior mesenteric artery (black arrows). The mass proved to be a conglomerate of neoplastic lymph nodes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g11a.jpeg" height="1261" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Variations in the CT appearance of lymphoma. Disseminated lymphoma in a 78-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> images show an infiltrative mass (white arrows) that surrounds mesenteric vessels (black arrows) and a desmoplastic reaction in the left side of the mesentery. The extent of the primary lesion, vascular involvement, and bowel abnormality are best depicted in <b>b</b>. Thickening of small-bowel loops (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) is suggestive of ischemic changes. The differential diagnosis based on these findings included sclerosing mesenteritis and carcinoid tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g11b.jpeg" height="1692" width="1543" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Variations in the CT appearance of lymphoma. Disseminated lymphoma in a 78-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> images show an infiltrative mass (white arrows) that surrounds mesenteric vessels (black arrows) and a desmoplastic reaction in the left side of the mesentery. The extent of the primary lesion, vascular involvement, and bowel abnormality are best depicted in <b>b</b>. Thickening of small-bowel loops (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) is suggestive of ischemic changes. The differential diagnosis based on these findings included sclerosing mesenteritis and carcinoid tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g12a.jpeg" height="1400" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Focal metastases. Poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in a 59-year-old man with an 8-month history of abdominal pain. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> images show a partially necrotic solid mesenteric mass (arrows) with associated fat stranding in the mesentery and induration and inflammation of the adjacent jejunum (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). The mass, which is centered in the small-bowel mesentery, has infiltrated the adjacent small-bowel wall, a finding best appreciated in <b>b</b>. The differential diagnosis included carcinoid tumor, lymphoma, gastrointestinal stromal tumor (less likely), metastases, necrotic nodes, and abscess. Biopsy results showed poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with lymphovascular and perineural invasion. Results of immunostaining were suggestive of pancreatic or gastric origin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g12b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1385" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Focal metastases. Poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in a 59-year-old man with an 8-month history of abdominal pain. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> images show a partially necrotic solid mesenteric mass (arrows) with associated fat stranding in the mesentery and induration and inflammation of the adjacent jejunum (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). The mass, which is centered in the small-bowel mesentery, has infiltrated the adjacent small-bowel wall, a finding best appreciated in <b>b</b>. The differential diagnosis included carcinoid tumor, lymphoma, gastrointestinal stromal tumor (less likely), metastases, necrotic nodes, and abscess. Biopsy results showed poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with lymphovascular and perineural invasion. Results of immunostaining were suggestive of pancreatic or gastric origin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g13x.jpeg" height="1512" width="1373" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Focal metastases. Metastatic melanoma in a 47-year-old woman with abdominal pain. Coronal VR image demonstrates a mildly enhancing lobulated mesenteric mass <i>(M)</i> that abuts the small bowel and peripheral branches of the superior mesenteric artery and that is surrounded by enlarged lymph nodes (arrows). At resection, the 9-cm mass was found to consist of multiple matted nodes due to metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g14x.jpeg" height="1476" width="1442" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Diffuse metastases. Poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in a 65-year-old man. Coronal VR image depicts the full extent of mesenteric disease, with diffuse tumor nodules. Nodules also were found in the omentum and retroperitoneum (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g15x.jpeg" height="1484" width="1494" aria-labelledby="F15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15.</b>  Diffuse metastases. Peritoneal carcinomatosis due to colon cancer in a 57-year-old man with symptoms of small-bowel obstruction. Coronal VR image fully depicts the disease features, including ascites, enhancing peritoneum (arrowheads), and mesenteric infiltration by the tumor (white arrows), as well as a hepatic metastasis (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g16a.jpeg" height="1638" width="1568" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Plexiform neurofibroma in a 13-year-old girl with neurofibromatosis and abdominal pain. Coronal VR images show a large, hypoattenuating, lobulated mass (white arrows) that has displaced the bowel and encased and stretched the mesenteric vessels (black arrows in <b>b</b>). The diagnosis was confirmed at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g16b.jpeg" height="1710" width="1628" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Plexiform neurofibroma in a 13-year-old girl with neurofibromatosis and abdominal pain. Coronal VR images show a large, hypoattenuating, lobulated mass (white arrows) that has displaced the bowel and encased and stretched the mesenteric vessels (black arrows in <b>b</b>). The diagnosis was confirmed at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g17x.jpeg" height="1601" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Desmoid tumor in a 55-year-old man after colectomy for familial polyposis coli. The patient also had a history of desmoid tumors. Coronal VR image shows a large desmoid (arrows) that has infiltrated the mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g18a.jpeg" height="1501" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Carcinoid tumor of the mesentery in a 66-year-old man. Coronal VR images show a calcified mass <i>(C)</i> with desmoplastic reaction, encasement of the superior mesenteric artery branches (white arrow in <b>a</b>), near-occlusion of the superior mesenteric vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), and invasion (black arrow in <b>b</b>) of the adjacent small bowel <i>(SB)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g18b.jpeg" height="1337" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Carcinoid tumor of the mesentery in a 66-year-old man. Coronal VR images show a calcified mass <i>(C)</i> with desmoplastic reaction, encasement of the superior mesenteric artery branches (white arrow in <b>a</b>), near-occlusion of the superior mesenteric vein (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), and invasion (black arrow in <b>b</b>) of the adjacent small bowel <i>(SB)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g19a.jpeg" height="1417" width="1602" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Carcinoid tumor with hepatic metastases in a 77-year-old man. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and MIP <b>(b)</b> images depict a 3.5-cm calcified mesenteric mass (white arrows) with encasement of the distal superior mesenteric artery (arrowheads) and superior mesenteric vein (not shown) and with desmoplastic reaction (black arrows). The vascular encasement and desmoplastic reaction are most conspicuous in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g19b.jpeg" height="1417" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Carcinoid tumor with hepatic metastases in a 77-year-old man. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and MIP <b>(b)</b> images depict a 3.5-cm calcified mesenteric mass (white arrows) with encasement of the distal superior mesenteric artery (arrowheads) and superior mesenteric vein (not shown) and with desmoplastic reaction (black arrows). The vascular encasement and desmoplastic reaction are most conspicuous in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g20x.jpeg" height="1494" width="1492" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Mimic of carcinoid tumor. Coronal VR image obtained in an 80-year-old asymptomatic man shows a 4-cm calcified stellate enhancing mesenteric mass (arrows) with desmoplastic reaction, small-bowel tethering, and bowel-wall ischemia, typical features of a carcinoid tumor. Exploratory laparotomy showed encasement of the superior mesenteric artery and superior mesenteric vein. Pathologic analysis demonstrated chronic inflammation, fibrosis, and fat necrosis, findings indicative of sclerosing mesenteritis, with no evidence of carcinoid tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g21x.jpeg" height="1374" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21.</b>  Conglomerate lymph node mass in a 44-year-old woman with HIV infection complicated by <i>M avium intracellulare</i> complex. Coronal VR image shows hypoattenuating adenopathy (arrows) that has infiltrated the mesentery. The focal area of high attenuation within the nodal mass likely represents a surgical clip.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g22x.jpeg" height="1588" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22.</b>  Immune reconstitution inflammatory syndrome in a 43-year-old HIV-positive woman with a history of <i>Mycobacterium simiae</i> infection and with new onset of abdominal pain 1 month after beginning HAART. Coronal VR image demonstrates a mildly heterogeneous solid mesenteric mass (arrows). US-guided percutaneous biopsy yielded a granulomatous inflammatory cellular infiltrate containing numerous acid-fast organisms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g23a.jpeg" height="1022" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Intraabdominal abscesses and lymph node necrosis in a 37-year-old HIV-negative woman with recurrent abdominal pain over the course of several years. Suppurative lymphadenitis was found at pathologic analysis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> CT images show multiple mesenteric abscesses (arrowheads), the extent of which is well depicted in <b>b</b>. Repeated specimen cultures were negative for bacteria (including acid-fast bacilli) and fungi. After reviewing the medical history and the results of pathologic analyses, the infectious disease specialist concluded that the findings were indicative of sterile abscess syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g23b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1432" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Intraabdominal abscesses and lymph node necrosis in a 37-year-old HIV-negative woman with recurrent abdominal pain over the course of several years. Suppurative lymphadenitis was found at pathologic analysis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> CT images show multiple mesenteric abscesses (arrowheads), the extent of which is well depicted in <b>b</b>. Repeated specimen cultures were negative for bacteria (including acid-fast bacilli) and fungi. After reviewing the medical history and the results of pathologic analyses, the infectious disease specialist concluded that the findings were indicative of sterile abscess syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g24a.jpeg" height="1457" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24a.</b>  Bowel perforation. Perforated jejunum in a 69-year-old woman with abdominal pain. Coronal MPR <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> CT images show stranding in the mesentery around the jejunum (arrows) with extraluminal air (arrowheads in <b>a</b>), a feature best depicted on axial and MPR images. Perforation due to jejunal diverticulitis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F24A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g24b.jpeg" height="1492" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24b.</b>  Bowel perforation. Perforated jejunum in a 69-year-old woman with abdominal pain. Coronal MPR <b>(a)</b> and coronal VR <b>(b)</b> CT images show stranding in the mesentery around the jejunum (arrows) with extraluminal air (arrowheads in <b>a</b>), a feature best depicted on axial and MPR images. Perforation due to jejunal diverticulitis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F24B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g25a.jpeg" height="1570" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F25A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25a.</b>  Bowel perforation. Perforated ileum in a 33-year-old man with steroid-dependent Crohn disease and right-lower-quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial image shows an ileal segment with adjacent mesenteric inflammation (arrows), a finding suggestive of microperforation. <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image shows the full extent of disease, including a long segment of actively inflamed distal ileum with mucosal hyperemia (black arrows), the comb sign in the adjacent mesentery (arrowheads), and the region of microperforation in the more proximal ileum (white arrows). A mesenteric abscess was found at surgery, and two areas of ileal perforation were identified at pathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F25A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g25b.jpeg" height="1204" width="1440" aria-labelledby="F25B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25b.</b>  Bowel perforation. Perforated ileum in a 33-year-old man with steroid-dependent Crohn disease and right-lower-quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial image shows an ileal segment with adjacent mesenteric inflammation (arrows), a finding suggestive of microperforation. <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image shows the full extent of disease, including a long segment of actively inflamed distal ileum with mucosal hyperemia (black arrows), the comb sign in the adjacent mesentery (arrowheads), and the region of microperforation in the more proximal ileum (white arrows). A mesenteric abscess was found at surgery, and two areas of ileal perforation were identified at pathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F25B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g26a.jpeg" height="1584" width="1509" aria-labelledby="F26A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26a.</b>  Severe colitis necessitating hospitalization and intravenous steroid therapy in a 30-year-old man with Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MPR image shows abnormal bowel wall (arrowheads) and prominent mesenteric vessels (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image obtained with interactive modifications shows bowel wall abnormality in the transverse colon (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Colorectal coronal VR image, optimized to depict the vasculature, provides comprehensive depiction of increased vascularity of the transverse mesocolon (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F26A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g26b.jpeg" height="1584" width="1478" aria-labelledby="F26B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26b.</b>  Severe colitis necessitating hospitalization and intravenous steroid therapy in a 30-year-old man with Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MPR image shows abnormal bowel wall (arrowheads) and prominent mesenteric vessels (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image obtained with interactive modifications shows bowel wall abnormality in the transverse colon (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Colorectal coronal VR image, optimized to depict the vasculature, provides comprehensive depiction of increased vascularity of the transverse mesocolon (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F26B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14c26c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1216" aria-labelledby="F26C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26c.</b>  Severe colitis necessitating hospitalization and intravenous steroid therapy in a 30-year-old man with Crohn disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MPR image shows abnormal bowel wall (arrowheads) and prominent mesenteric vessels (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal VR image obtained with interactive modifications shows bowel wall abnormality in the transverse colon (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Colorectal coronal VR image, optimized to depict the vasculature, provides comprehensive depiction of increased vascularity of the transverse mesocolon (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F26C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g27a.jpeg" height="1276" width="1584" aria-labelledby="F27A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27a.</b>  Sclerosing mesenteritis. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and sagittal MPR <b>(b)</b> images obtained in a 74-year-old man show the characteristic CT features of mesenteric panniculitis, including a left-sided region of patchy haziness (arrows) with a peripheral band of increased attenuation, small nodes, and stretching of the vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F27A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g27b.jpeg" height="1314" width="1194" aria-labelledby="F27B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27b.</b>  Sclerosing mesenteritis. Coronal VR <b>(a)</b> and sagittal MPR <b>(b)</b> images obtained in a 74-year-old man show the characteristic CT features of mesenteric panniculitis, including a left-sided region of patchy haziness (arrows) with a peripheral band of increased attenuation, small nodes, and stretching of the vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F27B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085113/asset/images/g09ma14g28x.jpeg" height="1728" width="1449" aria-labelledby="F28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 28.</b>  Sclerosing mesenteritis. Coronal VR image, obtained in a 58-year-old woman after oral glucocorticosteroid therapy, shows an enhancing mesenteric mass (arrow), inseparable from adjacent bowel and encasing the distal superior mesenteric artery and branches of the superior mesenteric vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085113&amp;id=F28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Meyers</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">MA</span></span>, Oliphant M, Berne AS, Feldberg MA. The peritoneal ligaments and mesenteries: pathways of intraabdominal spread of disease. <em>Radiology</em>1987; 163: 593–604.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiology.163.3.3575702">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3575702/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radiology&amp;publication_year=1987&amp;pages=593&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiology.163.3.3575702&amp;pmid=3575702">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">DeMeo</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">JH</span></span>, Fulcher AS, Austin RF. Anatomic CT demonstration of the peritoneal spaces, ligaments, and m